                    <div class="top-line__heading">
                        <div class="top-line__date">2014-2016</div>
                        <div class="top-line__heading-bold">Analysis</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="top-line__heading-big">
                        2014-2016 <span class="top-line__heading-text"></span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="top-line__bracket  top-line__bracket--right"><?php echo file_get_contents("parts/svg/bracket-right.svg"); ?></div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="line__segment line__segment--top"></div>
        <div class="line__segment line__segment--top"></div>
        <div class="line__segment line__segment--top">
            <div class="top-line__btn-wrapper">
                <div class="top-line__btn" data-btn="8">
                    <div class="top-line__bracket top-line__bracket-left"><?php echo file_get_contents("parts/svg/bracket-left.svg"); ?></div>
                    <div class="top-line__text-wrapper">
                        <div class="top-line__btn-line-left"></div>
                        <div class="top-line__text">
                            <p>When violence broke out in the South of Libya in 2017, Fayez al-Sarraj, Chairman of the Presidency Council and Prime Minister of the Government of National Accord, called upon the international community to intervene in order to put a and stop to the deteriorating security situation in the country. The call was rejected domestically by the House of Representatives and failed to generate traction internationally. Martin Kobler, the former Special Representative of the Secretary General and the Chief of the UN Support Mission in Libya (UNSMIL), commented that the international community “is keen on having no military intervention as an option to end Libya’s crisis, but rather will always push for dialogue as the only solution.”.<sup>33</sup></p>
                            <p>As fears were growing that another violent confrontation was about to happen, hopes of peace were renewed when the GNA Prime Minister Fayez al-Sarraj and Field Marshal Khalifa Haftaer of the Libyan National Army met in Dubai in May 2017 and July 2017 to agree on a ceasefire and elections to take place over the subsequent year.  In September 2017, the UN introduced a new Action Plan and facilitated talks on reducing the size of the GNA’s Presidential Council (PC) from nine to three and to introduce changes to the mandates of the legislature and the executive authorities. Eventually, the negotiating parties made some progress but failed to reach an agreement on the sequencing of the referendum and the elections. </p>
                            <p>In December 2017, the UN Security Council described the Libyan Political Agreement (LPA) as “the only viable framework to end the Libyan political crisis”.<sup>34</sup> Yet, Haftaer and the Libyan people had different opinions on the matter. Haftaer challenged the legitimacy of the LPA and its associated institutions, invokingciting the expiry of its term as the reason, therefore, the LPA-associated institutions were no longer legitimate. He called for elections, rejecting the subordination of the LNA to “any side regardless of its source of legitimacy” unless such body iswere elected by the Libyan people.<sup>35</sup> Neither elections nor the constitutional referendum took place in 2018. The fears of a unilateral military measure by Haftaer materialiszed in 2019 as the LNA moved militarily on the wWestern region. </p>
                            <p>Public confidence in the GNA continued to plummet throughout 2017. According to a 2017 poll conducted by IFES, seventy-four percent74% of Libyans had  very little to no confidence at all in the GNA. In the country’s wWest and Tripoli, confidence in the GNA wasstood at 25% and 15% respectively, while in the eEast and South it was 1% and 20% respectively.<sup>36</sup> Fifty-five percent  of Libyans favoured to postponinge the constitutional referendum and elections for a new interim president, while 24% supported a constitutional referendum based on the latest draft.<sup>37</sup></p>
                            <p>In 2018, another poll by IFES demonstrated an improved public confidence in the GNA and an increased support tofor holding a referendum before any other milestone. While the improvement in GNA confidence in the east was small (from 1 to 4%), it was pronounced in Tripoli (from 15% to 39%).<sup>38</sup> The percentage of Libyans who supported postponement of the referendum and elections decreased to 44%, while those wanting an immediate referendum almost doubled, to a hefty 42%.<sup>39</sup> Although these figures may have reflected the views of the civilian population, power elites have continued to have the upper hand on the course of the country’s future.</p>
                            <p>Despite the failure to set dates and a sequence for the elections and referendum, Libya’s High National Elections Commission (HNEC) set in motion the preparations for polls. By March 2018, a total of 2.4 million voters were registered, which is roughly 53% of the total number of eligible voters in Libya. Preparations hit a deadlock against the backdrop of  the growing political fissures and violence. </p>
                            <p>The institutional setup for the LPA was not working.<sup>40</sup> The UN-backed dialogue led to the reorganisation of power centres around the GNA, led by al-Sarraj and Khalifa Haftaer, head of the LNA.<sup>41</sup> There was an expectation that the political representatives involved in the LPA would  bring their armed and civilian constituencies to support the dialogue outcomes, t. Thus, representatives of armed groups were not invited to partakeparticipate in the negotiations.<sup>42</sup> This assumption not only proved wrong, but also caused serious security and legitimacy repercussions. </p>
                            <p>The GNA’s international legitimacy did not compensate for its lack of control over military forces to project power, which could have granted it an actual authority on the ground. This meant, that al-Sarraj needed to negotiate with armed groups controlling the capital, such as Misrata’s Halbus, and part of the Mahjub brigades and the Islamist militias, including the Special Deterrence Force,<sup>43</sup> so that the PC cancould operate from Tripoli. Most of the militias ended up backing the GNA and the PC for purely self-serving reasons.<sup>44</sup> By mid- 2018, the militias backing the GNA played a dubious economic role, blurring legitimate and illegitimate activities. They diverted public funds throughby pressuring managers of commercial banks and manipulated letters of credit to finance their activities. Meanwhile, the GNA stood powerless unable to stop them. In short, they sought to protect their own economic interests and grow their influence over the political institutions.<sup>45</sup></p>
